{{wikipedia|dab=Academy (disambiguation)|mul=Academy}}

===Etymology===
* First attested in 1474.
* {{sense|any school}} First attested by the 16th century.
* {{etyl|fr}} {{term|académie|lang=fr}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|academia|acadēmīa|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc}} {{term|lang=grc|Ἀκαδημία|tr=Akadēmia}}, a grove of trees and gymnasium outside of Athens where [[w:Plato|Plato]] taught; from the name of the supposed former owner of that estate, the [[w:Attica|Attic]] hero [[w:Akademos|Akademos]]. Compare [[academe]], [[academia]], [[Akademeia]].

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ə.ˈkæd.ə.mi/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/@"k{d@mi/}}
* {{audio|en-us-academy.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|academ|ies}}

# A society of [[learned]] men united for the [[advancement]] of the arts and sciences, and literature, or some particular art or science
#: ''the French '''Academy'''; the American '''Academy''' of Arts and Sciences; '''academies''' of literature and [[philology]].''
# A school or place of training in which some special art is taught
#: ''the military '''academy''' at West Point; a riding '''academy'''; the '''Academy''' of Music.''
#*{{quote-book|year=1956|author=[[w:Delano Ames|Delano Ames]]|title=Crime out of Mind|chapter=9|url=http://openlibrary.org/works/OL5915292W|passage=Rudolf was the bold, bad Baron of traditional melodrama.  Irene was young, as pretty as a picture, fresh from a music '''academy''' in England.  He was the scion of an ancient noble family; she an orphan without money or friends.}}
# An [[institution]] for the study of higher learning; a [[college]] or a [[university]]; typically a private school.
# Popularly, a school, or [[seminary]] of learning, holding a rank between a college and a common school.
# A place of [[training]]; a school.
#* {{quote-book|title=The history of England from the revolution in 1688, to the death of George II|page=449|author=[[w:Tobias Smollett|Tobias Smollett]]|year_published=1805|passage=The artists of London had long maintained a private '''academy''' for improvement in the art of drawing from living figures|year=1760-5}}
#* {{quote-book|title=The life of David Hume|author=[[w:David Hume|David Hume]]|passage=In this year 1633, I became acquainted with Nicholas Fiske, licentiate in physic, who was born in Suffolk, near Framingham* Castle, of very good parentage, who educated him at country schools, until he was fit for the university; but he went not to the '''academy''', studying at home both astrology and physic, which he afterwards practised in Colchester; and there was well acquainted with Dr Gilbert, who wrote "De Magnete".|year=1776|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=0c5hLAjitzYC&pg=PA140&dq=inauthor:%22david+hume%22+%22academy%22+-%22French+academy%22+-intitle:History&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FekmT43AN8K00AG7zcHKCA&ved=0CF8Q6AEwBg#v=onepage&q&f=false}}
# {{context|with ''the''|without reference to any specific academy}} [[academia|Academia]].
# A body of established opinion in a particular field, regarded as authoritative.

